article.description: Seimone Augustus had 22 points to lead top-ranked LSU past Mississippi 82-58.
article.headline: Augustus leads LSU with 22 points
article.linkText: Tenacious 'D': No. 1 LSU stifles Ole Miss in rout
article.story:
OXFORD, Miss. (AP) -- LSU is back at No. 1 for the first time in nearly a month, and this time the Tigers aren't letting themselves get caught up in their ranking.

"This particular team is good at keeping things in perspective," LSU coach Pokey Chatman said. "Every night out, regardless of ranking, they're very methodical in their approach."

Seimone Augustus had 22 points to lead four Tigers in double figures in an 82-58 victory over Mississippi on Thursday night.

LSU (20-1, 7-0) made nearly 53 percent of its shots, held the Rebels to 28 percent shooting and kept pace with No. 5 Tennessee as the only unbeaten teams in Southeastern Conference play.

Augustus, second in the league in scoring with a 20.2-point average, was 11-of-20 from the field and scored 12 points in the second half.

"Luckily, I hit more than I missed," Augustus said.

Sylvia Fowles had 14 points and 13 rebounds and Scholanda Hoston added 13 points on four 3-pointers for LSU, which only briefly trailed in the first half and didn't let Ole Miss get closer than seven in the second.

Wendlyn Jones added 11 points and 11 rebounds for the Tigers, who won their ninth straight over Ole Miss.

Temeka Johnson had 11 assists and tied the SEC record for career assists with 816, a mark set by Florida's Camille Ratledge from 1986-90.

Carletta Brown had 17 points and Arminitie Price added 15 for Ole Miss (15-6, 5-3). Amber Watts -- coming off a 21-point game at Arkansas -- was held to one and was in foul trouble all night.

"We just don't have the experienced depth that we can put a senior on the bench," Ole Miss coach Carol Ross said.

It was LSU's first game at No. 1 since falling from the top spot last month, and the Tigers weren't about to relinquish it this time.

The SEC's stingiest defense held Ole Miss to one field goal over a nine-minute span and held the Rebels to 29 percent shooting in the first half.

"We just struggled out of the gate to be aggressive," Ross said. "We have to take the game to people. We can't sit back. ... It takes a lot of energy to get that turned. They popped us in the mouth, and it got away again."

Quianna Chaney's 3-pointer at the buzzer capped a half in which the Tigers shot 48 percent and led 40-26.

LSU entered allowing opponents 51.4 points and 34 percent shooting from the field, both tops in the conference.

The Tigers "are fast, they're big, they're athletic. But they're cerebral basketball players," Chatman said.

That dominance helped LSU return to the top spot this week, after former No. 1 Duke lost to North Carolina. The Tigers previously held the top spot for six weeks before an overtime loss to Rutgers on Jan. 5.

Ole Miss was off to its best start in nine years, duplicating its 15-5 mark to begin the 1995-96 season.
